SKILL|spike|"Throwaway experiments to validate an idea before build."
STEP|1|The answer is knowable from docs or reading code — just do research, don't build
STEP|2|The work is production path — use the `plan` skill instead
STEP|3|The idea is already validated — jump straight to implementation
STEP|4|Spike types:**
STEP|5|**standard** — one approach answering one question
STEP|6|**comparison** — same question, different approaches (shared number, letter suffix `a`/`b`/`c`)
STEP|7|Good spike questions:** specific feasibility with observable output.
STEP|8|Bad spike questions:** too broad, no observable output, or just "read the docs about X".
STEP|9|Order by risk.** The spike most likely to kill the idea runs first. No point prototyping the easy parts if the hard part doesn't work.
STEP|10|Skip decomposition** only if the user already knows exactly what they want to spike and says so. Then take their idea as a single spike.
STEP|11|**Brief it.** 2-3 sentences: what this spike is, why it matters, key risk.
STEP|12|**Surface competing approaches** if there's real choice:
STEP|13|**Pick one.** State why. If 2+ are credible, build quick variants within the spike.
STEP|14|**Skip research** for pure logic with no external dependencies.
STEP|15|`web_search("python websocket streaming libraries 2025")` — find candidates
STEP|16|`web_extract(urls=["https://websockets.readthedocs.io/..."])` — read the actual docs (returns markdown)
STEP|17|`terminal("pip show websockets \| grep Version")` — check what's installed in the project's venv
STEP|18|Bias toward something the user can interact with.** Spikes fail when the only output is a log line that says "it works." The user wants to *feel* the spike working. Default choices, in order of prefer
STEP|19|A runnable CLI that takes input and prints observable output
STEP|20|A minimal HTML page that demonstrates the behavior
STEP|21|A small web server with one endpoint
STEP|22|A unit test that exercises the question with recognizable assertions
STEP|23|Depth over speed.** Never declare "it works" after one happy-path run. Test edge cases. Follow surprising findings. The verdict is only trustworthy when the investigation was honest.
STEP|24|Avoid** unless the spike specifically requires it: complex package management, build tools/bundlers, Docker, env files, config systems. Hardcode everything — it's a spike.
STEP|25|Building one spike** — a typical tool sequence:
STEP|26|Parallel comparison spikes (002a / 002b) — delegate.** When two approaches can run in parallel and both need real engineering (not 10-line prototypes), fan out with `delegate_task`:
STEP|27|...
STEP|28|...
STEP|29|...
STEP|30|...
STEP|31|VALIDATED** = the core question was answered yes, with evidence.
STEP|32|PARTIAL** = it works under constraints X, Y, Z — document them.
STEP|33|INVALIDATED** = doesn't work, for this reason. This is a successful spike.
STEP|34|Winner:** pdfjs for our use case. Camelot if we need table-first extraction later.
STEP|35|**Integration risks** — two validated spikes that touch the same resource but were tested independently
STEP|36|**Data handoffs** — spike A's output was assumed compatible with spike B's input; never proven
STEP|37|**Gaps in the vision** — capabilities assumed but unproven
STEP|38|**Alternative approaches** — different angles for PARTIAL or INVALIDATED spikes
STEP|39|Create `spikes/` (or `.planning/spikes/` if the user is using GSD conventions) in the repo root
STEP|40|One dir per spike: `NNN-descriptive-name/`
STEP|41|`README.md` per spike captures question, approach, results, verdict
STEP|42|Keep the code throwaway — a spike that takes 2 days to "clean up for production" was a bad spike
